\begin_layout Chapter
Measurable functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Limits of sets and their indicator functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we embark on a general description of measurable functions, it's
 useful to look at a special kind of function: the indicator function of
 a set.
 These functions are special, because they are essentially the building
 blocks of all important functions in measure theory.
 In fact, indicator functions of sets are the key to linking abstract measure
 theory on one hand, to the theory of integration on the other.
 As we shall later see, this link is actually an equivalence: measures and
 integrals are equivalent objects, and so, in the context of this theory,
 sets and their indicator functions are also in some sense equivalent.
 While the full scope of this equivalence will only become salient when
 we discuss integration, this section will shed some light on why we perhaps
 should expect this 
\emph on
ex-ante
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:indicatorFunction"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary subset.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathds{1}_{A}:\mathcal{X}\longrightarrow\left\{ 0,1\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathds{1}_{A}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
1 & x\in A\\
0 & x\notin A
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

is called the 
\emph on
indicator function 
\emph default
of set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algebra of sets implies a corresponding Boolean algebra for indicator
 functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Fact
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fact:indicatorFunctionsFiniteOperations"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be arbitrary and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{1}_{A},\mathds{1}_{B}$
\end_inset

 be their respective indicator functions.
 Then the indicator function of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $C:=A\cup B$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathds{1}_{C}=\max\left\{ \mathds{1}_{A},\mathds{1}_{B}\right\} =\mathds{1}_{A}+\mathds{1}_{B}-\mathds{1}_{A}\mathds{1}_{B}
\]

\end_inset

where the maximum is taken pointwise.
 Similarly, the indicator function for set 
\begin_inset Formula $D:=A\cap B$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathds{1}_{D}=\min\left\{ \mathds{1}_{A},\mathds{1}_{B}\right\} =\mathds{1}_{A}\mathds{1}_{B}.
\]

\end_inset

The indicator function for 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{C}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathds{1}_{A^{C}}=1-\mathds{1}_{A}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 are disjoint, then the indicator function of their union is simply the
 sum of their individual indicators, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathds{1}_{A\cup B}=\mathds{1}_{A}+\mathds{1}_{B}.
\]

\end_inset

We can extend these facts to describe indicator functions of arbitrary unions
 and intersections of sets in the obvious way
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:indicatorFunctionsArbitraryOperations"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary index set and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{i}\right\} _{i\in\mathcal{I}}\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be subsets with indicator functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathds{1}_{A_{i}}\right\} _{i\in\mathcal{I}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, the indicator function for 
\begin_inset Formula $B:=\bigcup_{i\in\mathcal{I}}A_{i}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathds{1}_{B}=\sup_{i\in\mathcal{I}}\mathds{1}_{A_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

where the supremum is taken pointwise.
 Similarly, the indicator function for 
\begin_inset Formula $C:=\bigcap_{i\in\mathcal{I}}A_{i}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathds{1}_{C}=\inf_{i\in\mathcal{I}}\mathds{1}_{A_{i}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We provide the argument for 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

; the argument for 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is analagous.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathds{1}_{B}\left(x\right)=1 & \Longleftrightarrow x\in\bigcup_{i\in\mathcal{I}}A_{i}\\
 & \Longleftrightarrow x\in A_{i_{0}}\textrm{ for some }i_{0}\in\mathcal{I}\\
 & \Longleftrightarrow\mathds{1}_{A_{i_{0}}}=1\text{ for some }i_{0}\in\mathcal{I}\\
 & \Longleftrightarrow\sup_{i\in\mathcal{I}}\mathds{1}_{A_{i}}=1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which completes the argument.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These arguments appear to be rather pedantic, but they are key to defining
 limiting operations on sets.
 With a background in undergraduate calculus, it can be quite cumbersome
 to think of a sequence of sets converging to another set.
 However, it is quite straightforward to imagine the pointwise convergence
 of a sequence of 
\emph on
indicator functions 
\emph default
of sets.
 For example, we have what appears to be a fairly daunting definition for
 the limit of a sequence of sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:limSupInfSets"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{i}\right\} _{i\in\N}$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\mathcal{X}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the limit superior of the sequence is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\limsup_{n\to\infty}A_{n}:=\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}\bigcup_{i=n}^{\infty}A_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

Similarly, the limit inferior of the sequence is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\liminf_{n\to\infty}A_{n}:=\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}\bigcap_{i=n}^{\infty}A_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\limsup_{n\to\infty}A_{n}=\liminf_{n\to\infty}A_{n}$
\end_inset

 then the limit of the sequence is defined and is equal to the limit superior
 and inferior i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty}A_{n}:=\limsup_{n\to\infty}A_{n}=\liminf_{n\to\infty}A_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
While these definitions appear arbitrary, they demarcate important concepts
 in both analysis and probability.
 To unpack the intuition, let's try to understand what it means for an element
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 to be in 
\begin_inset Formula $\limsup_{n\to\infty}A_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}\bigcup_{i=n}^{\infty}A_{i}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcup_{i=n}^{\infty}A_{i}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

.
 That it is to say, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

, there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This essentially says that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is in infinitely many of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{i}\right\} _{i\in\N}$
\end_inset

.
 In the language of probability, the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\limsup_{n\to\infty}A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the event of outcomes that occur infinitely often in the collection
 of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{i}\right\} _{i\in\N}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
On the other hand, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\liminf_{n\to\infty}A_{n},$
\end_inset

then there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{0}\in\N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A_{i}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq n_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\liminf_{n\to\infty}A_{n}\subseteq\limsup_{n\to\infty}A_{n}$
\end_inset

 which mirrors the domination condition for limit superiors and inferiors
 of sequences of real numbers or real functions.
 So when does equality hold? Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{i}\right\} _{i\in\N}$
\end_inset

 is an increasing sequence of sets
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\limsup_{n\to\infty}A_{n} & =\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}\bigcup_{i=n}^{\infty}A_{i}\\
 & =\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}\bigcup_{i=1}^{\infty}A_{i}\\
 & =\bigcup_{i=1}^{\infty}A_{i}\\
 & =\bigcup_{i=1}^{\infty}\bigcap_{n=i}^{\infty}A_{n}\\
 & =\liminf_{i\to\infty}A_{i}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the second and fourth equalitiies follow from the increasing nature
 of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that the continuity from below condition described in Proposition
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:measureProperties"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is in fact bona-fide continuity.
 After developing the theory of integration, we will (seemingly) generalize
 this continuity result to measurable functions in the form of the famous
 
\emph on
monotone convergence theorem
\emph default
.
 Of course, once we know that measures and integrals are essentially the
 same objects, it will be clear that continuity from below and monotone
 convergence are two sides of the same coin.
 While this result is better known in it's integral formulation, there's
 another result that is perhaps better known in its measure-theoretic formulatio
n: the Borel-Cantelli lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
First Borel-Cantelli lemma
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:borelCantelli"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{F},\mu\right)$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary measure space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{i}\right\} _{i\in\N}\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of sets.
 If
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\mu\left(A_{i}\right)<\infty
\]

\end_inset

then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu\left(\limsup_{i\to\infty}A_{i}\right)=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Define by 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{n}:=\bigcup_{i=n}^{\infty}A_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 It's clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ B_{n}\right\} _{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

 is a decreasing sequence of sets.
 More over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(B_{1}\right)=\mu\left(\bigcup_{i\in\N}A_{i}\right)\leq\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\mu\left(A_{i}\right)<\infty$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hyperref[cor:countableSubadditivity]{subadditivity}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and so, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is finite on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ B_{n}\right\} _{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

, we can apply Propositions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:measureProperties"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:equivalenceContinuityMeasures"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to establish
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\left(\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}B_{n}\right) & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\mu\left(B_{n}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\text{\ensuremath{\mu\left(\bigcup_{i=n}^{\infty}A_{i}\right)}}\\
 & \leq\lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{i=n}^{\infty}\mu\left(A_{i}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\left[\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\mu\left(A_{i}\right)-\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}\mu\left(A_{i}\right)\right]\\
 & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the inequality follows from subadditivity and the last equality is
 due to the the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in\N}\mu\left(A_{i}\right)<\infty$
\end_inset

 along with the fact that a sequence and its tail have the same limit.
\end_layout

