\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:limSupInfIndicator"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{i}\right\} _{i\in\N}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \indicate_{A_{i}}\right\} _{i\in\N}$
\end_inset

 be their corresponding indicator functions.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\limsup_{n\to\infty}\indicate_{A_{n}}=\indicate_{\limsup_{n\to\infty}A_{n}}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\liminf_{n\to\infty}\indicate_{A_{n}}=\indicate_{\liminf_{n\to\infty}A_{n}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We prove the first assertion as the second one follows by the same argument.
 Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\limsup_{n\to\infty}\indicate_{A_{n}} & =\inf_{n\in\N}\left\{ \sup_{i\geq n}\indicate_{A_{i}}\right\} \\
 & =\inf_{n\in\N}\left\{ \indicate_{\bigcup_{i\geq n}A_{i}}\right\} \\
 & =\indicate_{\bigcap_{n\in\N}\bigcup_{i\geq n}A_{i}}\\
 & =\indicate_{\liminf_{n\to\infty}A_{n}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the second and third equalities follow by Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:indicatorFunctionsArbitraryOperations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By now, you should have begun to appreciate that indicator functions are
 essentially functional equivalents of the sets they indicate: sets and
 their indicator functioins are just two representations of the same object.
 This is not particularly suprising, given that sets are defined by their
 membership and indicator functions describe membership.
 In this context, it should then not be suprising that indicator functions
 of 
\emph on
measurable sets 
\emph default
are 
\emph on
measurable functions
\emph default
,
\emph on
 
\emph default
even though we have not yet described the latter concept yet.
 This is indeed true, and moreover, any non-negative measurable function
 can be built by taking a limit of a linear combination of indicators of
 sets.
 But before we can show this, we should first define what a measurable function
 is!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:measurableFunction"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\mathcal{F}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{Y},\mathcal{G}\right)$
\end_inset

 be two measurable spaces.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:\mathcal{X}\longrightarrow\mathcal{Y}
\]

\end_inset

is called 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}/\mathcal{G}-$
\end_inset

measurable 
\emph default
if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $G\in\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}\left[G\right]\in\mathcal{F}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
This definition also resembles a continuity condition; indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 were topologies rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-$
\end_inset

algebras, this would be the definition of a continuous function.
 It turns out that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 are Borel 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-$
\end_inset

algebras, then continuity implies measurability: this is a fact that we
 establish in the next section.
 Moreover, all measurable functions are in some sense 
\emph on
almost 
\emph default
continuous: we make this notion precise when we discuss the deep connections
 between topology and measure theory in Appendix A.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Later in these notes, we will stop writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}/\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 explicitly and let the reader infer the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-$
\end_inset

algebras in play from the context.
\end_layout

