\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Armed with our definition of measurable functions, we are ready to discuss
 interesting examples of such functions along with their properties.
 First, we establish that the measurability of a sets and its indicator
 function is indeed equivalent, as we had guessed earlier
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:measurableSetsFunctions"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\mathcal{F}\right)$
\end_inset

 be a measurable space.
 Then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is measurable (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

) if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\indicate_{A}:\mathcal{X}\longrightarrow\left\{ 0,1\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}/2^{\left\{ 0,1\right\} }-$
\end_inset

measurable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 and observe that if 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\indicate_{A}^{-1}\left[B\right]=\X\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{1\}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\indicate_{A}^{-1}\left[B\right]=A\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\indicate_{A}^{-1}\left[B\right]=A^{C}\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\indicate_{A}^{-1}\left[B\right]=\emptyset\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Conversely, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\indicate_{A}$
\end_inset

 is measurable and notice how 
\begin_inset Formula $A=f^{-1}\left[\left\{ 1\right\} \right]\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 which completes the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, measurability of our function was easy to establish because
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-$
\end_inset

algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\left\{ 0,1\right\} }$
\end_inset

 could be explicitly enumerated.
 Generally, this is not possible as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-$
\end_inset

algebras can be extremely large.
 Nevertheless, it is possible establish measurability using a smaller class
 of sets in the target 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-$
\end_inset

algebra; this is the crux of generating class arguments which we discusss
 more abstractly in the next section.
 Even the simplest of such arguments can be quite powerful, as we shall
 see with the following result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:genericGeneratingClassArgument"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Generic generating class argument
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\mathcal{F}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{Y},\mathcal{G}\right)$
\end_inset

 be measurable spaces and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}\subseteq\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 be a collection of sets such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\left(\mathcal{E}\right)=\mathcal{G}.$
\end_inset

 A function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:\X\longrightarrow\mathcal{Y}
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}/\mathcal{G}-$
\end_inset

measurable if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}\left[E\right]\in\mathcal{F}
\]

\end_inset

for every 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{E}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is measurable, then by definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\left[E\right]\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}\subseteq\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\left[E\right]\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 and define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{D}=\left\{ G\in\mathcal{G}\mid f^{-1}\left[G\right]\in\mathcal{F}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

By assumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}\subseteq\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 and with a little effort we can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 is in fact a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-$
\end_inset

algebra, which then shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}=\sigma\left(\mathcal{E}\right)\subseteq\sigma\left(\mathcal{D}\right)=\mathcal{D}.$
\end_inset

 First, it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}\left[\emptyset\right]=\emptyset\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Next, for any 
