\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}^{+}\left(\X,\mathcal{F}\right)$
\end_inset

 to denote the set of all non-negative (extended) real-valued Borel-measurable
 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\mathcal{F}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:simpleFunction"

\end_inset

 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $s:\mathcal{X}\longrightarrow\R$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\emph on
simple function 
\emph default
if its range is a finite subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\R.$
\end_inset

 It can be represented as an aggregation of indicator functions as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\sum_{i=1}^{k}\alpha_{i}\indicate_{A_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \alpha_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{k}\in\R$
\end_inset

 is the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{k}\subseteq\R$
\end_inset

 partitions the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 into preimages of the range.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be clear that a non-negative simple function 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{M^{+}}\left(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{F}\right)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ A_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{k}\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

; the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

if
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 part follows directly from Corollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cor:examplesBinaryOpsMeasFunc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 To see the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

only if
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 part, note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is measurable then 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{-1}\left[\left\{ \alpha_{i}\right\} \right]=A_{i}\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 since singletons in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 are Borel sets.
 Denote the collection of these measurable simple functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\mathcal{F}\right)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{s}\left(\X,\mathcal{F}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then, we have shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{s}\left(\X,\mathcal{F}\right)\subset\mathcal{M^{+}}\left(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{F}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It turns out that we can make a stronger claim: the measurable simple functions
 are in some sense 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dense
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the space of non-negative measurable functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:simpleFunctionMonotoneConvergence"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{M^{+}}\left(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{F}\right)$
\end_inset

 be arbitrary.
 Then there exists a sequence of simple measurable functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ f_{n}\right\} _{n\in\N}\in M_{s}\left(\X,\mathcal{F}\right)$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{n}\leq f_{n+1}
\]

\end_inset

pointwise for every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty}f_{n}=f
\]

\end_inset

where the limit is taken pointwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
It turns out that we can establish the existence of such functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 constructively.
 Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{n}\left(x\right):=\sum_{k=0}^{4^{n}-1}\frac{k}{2^{n}}\indicate_{\left\{ \frac{k}{2^{n}}\leq f\left(x\right)<\frac{k+1}{2^{n}}\right\} }+2^{n}\indicate_{\left\{ f\left(x\right)\geq2^{n}\right\} }
\]

\end_inset

and observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 are Borel-measurable simple functions (given the measurability of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

) and that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\leq f$
\end_inset

 pointwise by definition.
 Next, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \frac{k}{2^{n}}\right\} _{k=0}^{4^{n}}\subset\left\{ \frac{k}{2^{n+1}}\right\} _{k=0}^{4^{n+1}}$
\end_inset

 and fix 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\X$
\end_inset

 to be arbitrary.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{k_{0}}{2^{n}}\leq f\left(x_{0}\right)<\frac{k_{0}+1}{2^{n}}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{0}\in\left\{ 0,1,\ldots,4^{n}-1\right\} $
\end_inset

 then either 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{k_{0}}{2^{n}}=\frac{2k_{0}}{2^{n+1}}\leq f\left(x_{0}\right)<\frac{2k_{0}+1}{2^{n+1}}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2k_{0}+1}{2^{n+1}}\leq f\left(x_{0}\right)<\frac{2k_{0}+2}{2^{n+1}}=\frac{k_{0}+1}{2^{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 In either case,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{n}\left(x_{0}\right)=\frac{k_{0}}{2^{n}}\leq f_{n+1}\left(x_{0}\right)\leq\frac{2k_{0}+1}{2^{n+1}}
\]

\end_inset

by the definitions of our simple functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}.$
\end_inset

 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x_{0}\right)\geq2^{n}$
\end_inset

 then either 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x_{0}\right)\geq2^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 or there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{0}\in\left\{ 2^{2n+1},\ldots,4^{n+1}-1\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{k_{0}}{2^{n+1}}\leq f\left(x_{0}\right)<\frac{k_{0}+1}{2^{n+1}}.
\]

\end_inset

Again, in either case,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{n}\left(x_{0}\right)=2^{n}\leq\frac{k_{0}}{2^{n+1}}\leq f_{n+1}\left(x_{0}\right)\leq2^{n+1}
\]

\end_inset

which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\leq f_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 pointwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
To show convergence, again pick an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\X$
\end_inset

 and observe that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x_{0}\right)=\infty$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\left(x_{0}\right)=2^{n}\nearrow\infty=f\left(x_{0}\right).$
\end_inset

 Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x_{0}\right)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Then, since the natural numbers are not bounded above in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

, we know that there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{x_{0}}\in\N$
\end_inset

 such that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq n_{x_{0}}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x_{0}\right)<2^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for each such 
\begin_inset Formula $n,$
\end_inset

 there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}\in\left\{ 0,1,\ldots,4^{n}-1\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{k_{n}}{2^{n}}\leq f\left(x_{0}\right)<\frac{k_{n}+1}{2^{n}}\label{eq:pointwiseInequalitySimpleFunc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which would imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\left(x_{0}\right)=\frac{k_{n}}{2^{n}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq n_{x_{0}}.$
\end_inset

 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\leq f\left(x_{0}\right)-f_{n}\left(x_{0}\right)=f\left(x_{0}\right)-\frac{k_{n}}{2^{n}}\leq\frac{k_{n}+1}{2^{n}}-\frac{k_{n}}{2_{n}}=\frac{1}{2^{n}}
\]

\end_inset

where the first inequality is due to the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\leq f$
\end_inset

 pointwise and the second inequality is due to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pointwiseInequalitySimpleFunc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Taking limits then yields the result.
\end_layout

